      homework: [
        {
          question: "Complete the Digital Footprint Audit (from practice step 1). Submit your report: what you found, what you'd change, what you'd keep. Then make at least 2 changes (delete a post, adjust privacy settings, etc.) and write what you did and why.",
          solution: "Example:\n'Digital Footprint Audit Report:\n\nWhat I found:\n1. Google search: 3 results. One positive (school achievement listing), one neutral (my Instagram profile), one negative (a YouTube comment where I was rude to someone).\n2. Instagram: 15 posts. 12 are fine, 2 are borderline (silly faces that could be embarrassing later), 1 is a photo at a location I don't want public.\n3. YouTube comments: 5 total. 1 rude comment.\n4. Parent's social media: 2 photos of me at family events. One shows my school uniform clearly.\n\nWhat I changed:\n1. Deleted the rude YouTube comment. I'd written 'this video is garbage, worst tutorial ever' when the tutorial didn't work for me. Looking back, it was unnecessarily harsh. The creator put effort into that video.\n2. Asked Mom to restrict the Facebook photo with my school uniform to 'Friends only' instead of 'Public.' She agreed after I explained why.\n3. Made my Instagram account private. It was public before — anyone could see my posts. Now only approved followers can see them.\n4. Deleted the photo at the location I didn't want public. Not because it was bad, but because it showed where I hang out with friends.\n\nWhat I kept:\n1. School achievement listing — it's public record and positive.\n2. All other Instagram posts — they show my life, hobbies, and friendships.\n3. The neutral YouTube comments — they're constructive and polite.\n\nLesson: The audit took 30 minutes but revealed things I'd completely forgotten about. The rude comment especially — I'd posted it in 10 seconds of frustration but it's been public for 8 months. That's a long time for something I'm not proud of to be findable.\n\nGoing forward: I'll do this audit every 3 months. And I'll use the 'grandma test' before every post.'"
        },
        {
          question: "Create a 'Cyberbullying Response Guide' — a one-page Canva infographic that shows what to do if you or someone you know is being cyberbullied. Include: definition, types, immediate steps, how to get help, and resources (helplines, websites).",
          solution: "Example:\n'CYBERBULLYING RESPONSE GUIDE\n\nDefinition: Cyberbullying is using digital technology to harass, threaten, embarrass, or target another person. It includes: mean comments, spreading rumors, sharing embarrassing photos, exclusion from groups, and impersonation.\n\nTypes:\n- Harassment: Repeated mean messages or comments\n- Exclusion: Deliberately leaving someone out of group chats or activities\n- Outing: Sharing someone's secrets or private information\n- Impersonation: Pretending to be someone to post harmful things\n- Fraping: Posting inappropriate content on someone's account without permission\n\nImmediate Steps (if it's happening to you):\n1. DON'T respond — bullies want a reaction. Don't give them one.\n2. SCREENSHOT everything — save evidence before it's deleted.\n3. BLOCK the bully — on every platform.\n4. REPORT the content — use the platform's reporting tool.\n5. TELL a trusted adult — parent, teacher, counselor. You don't have to handle this alone.\n\nHow to Help a Friend:\n1. Listen without judging. Don't say 'just ignore it' — that minimizes their pain.\n2. Offer to screenshot and report together.\n3. Don't post about the drama publicly — it escalates things.\n4. Include them in real-world activities. Don't let them isolate.\n5. If they're in danger, tell an adult immediately.\n\nResources:\n- Childline India: 1800-5-9960 (free, 24/7)\n- National Cyberbullying Helpline: cyberbullying.org\n- Instagram Help Center: help.instagram.com (for reporting)\n- School counselor — always a safe option\n\nRemember: Cyberbullying is NEVER the victim's fault. The bully's behavior reflects their own problems, not your worth.'"
        },
        {
          question: "Write a 'Week-Long Digital Citizenship Challenge' for yourself. Each day, do one thing that makes you a better digital citizen. Log your actions. Examples: Don't share unverified info, compliment someone online, report harmful content, reduce screen time by 30 minutes, etc.",
          solution: "Example:\n'DIGITAL CITIZENSHIP CHALLENGE — Week Log\n\nMonday — Verification Day\nAction: Before sharing a WhatsApp forward about '5G causing health problems,' I searched for it on Google and checked WHO's website. Found it was false. Didn't share it.\nAlso: Reported a fake news post on Instagram that was spreading misinformation about vaccines.\n\nTuesday — Kindness Day\nAction: Left 3 genuine positive comments on classmates' Instagram posts. Not generic ('nice pic') but specific ('your drawing technique is really improving, the shading is great').\nAlso: Sent a thank-you message to a teacher who helped me last week.\n\nWednesday — Privacy Day\nAction: Reviewed privacy settings on Instagram, TikTok, and YouTube. Made TikTok private. Restricted YouTube comments on my videos to subscribers only.\nAlso: Asked 2 friends to delete photos of me from their social media (they had posted without asking).\n\nThursday — Balance Day\nAction: Tracked screen time. Usually 5 hours/day. Set a goal of 3.5 hours. Used Instagram's 'Daily Limit' feature to lock myself out after 1 hour of Instagram.\nAlso: Kept phone outside bedroom at night for the first time. Slept better.\n\nFriday — Upstander Day\nAction: Saw a classmate being made fun of in a group chat. Privately messaged them: 'That wasn't okay. I'm here if you want to talk.' Didn't confront the bullies publicly (would escalate).\nAlso: Reported a hateful comment on a YouTube video to the platform.\n\nSaturday — Creation Day\nAction: Instead of just consuming content, I created something positive. Made a Canva infographic about digital safety (from this course). Shared it on my Instagram story.\nAlso: Started a 'skills journal' where I write one thing I learned each day.\n\nSunday — Reflection Day\nAction: Reviewed the week. What went well? The privacy changes and screen time reduction felt good. What was hard? Not responding when someone was rude to me online (I wanted to clap back). What did I learn? Being a digital citizen is a daily practice, not a one-time thing.\n\nOverall: 7 days, 14 actions. Small things, but they add up. I feel more intentional about how I use technology.'"
        }
      ]
