          step: "Write Your Presentation Structure",
          instruction: "Write the structure for your 2-minute Demo Day presentation. Don't write a word-for-word script — write bullet points for each section:\n\n1. Hook (10s): What surprising statement will you open with?\n2. What (20s): What did you build? (Your website)\n3. Why (20s): Why does it matter?\n4. Demo (40s): What will you show? (Which pages, which projects)\n5. Lesson (20s): What's the biggest thing you learned?\n6. Close (10s): What's your final line?\n\nTime yourself reading it. Should be around 2 minutes.",
          example: "Example structure:\n'HOOK (10s): 'Three months ago, I didn't know how to build a website. Today, I have one that anyone in the world can visit.'\n\nWHAT (20s): 'I built a personal portfolio website using Google Sites. It has 4 pages: Home, About, Projects, and Hobbies. It showcases everything I've created in the Explorer level — digital stories, posters, infographics, and videos.'\n\nWHY (20s): 'Because every student should have a portfolio. Not just a report card — a real showcase of what they can create. My website proves that I can learn new tools, manage projects, and present my work to the world.'\n\nDEMO (40s): [Live walkthrough]\n- Show Home page → point to hero section\n- Click Projects → show 4 project cards\n- Click on the video → play 10 seconds\n- Click Hobbies → show the cooking photo\n- Point out: 'All images are optimised, all links work, it's mobile-friendly.'\n\nLESSON (20s): 'The biggest thing I learned isn't technical. It's that done is better than perfect. My first website version was ugly. But I published it, got feedback, and improved it. Every version got better.'\n\nCLOSE (10s): 'If a 12-year-old can build a website from scratch, what can you build?'\n\nTimed read-through: 1:55. Perfect.'"
