          solution: "Example peer review:\n'Reviewing Priya's portfolio:\n\n1. Best projects selected? ✓ Yes — 5 diverse projects showing different skills. No weak pieces.\n2. Clear captions? ✓ Yes — Each has title, type, tools, description, and lesson. Well-written.\n3. Order logical? Mostly ✓ — Chronological order shows growth, but the video at position 3 breaks the flow between the two Canva designs. Suggestion: Move the video to last so Canva projects are together.\n4. Images professional? ✓ Yes — All screenshots are optimised, well-cropped, and consistent in size.\n5. Portfolio statement? ✓ Strong — Clear, confident, mentions specific skills.\n\n2 Compliments:\n- The decision to include your earliest Canva poster alongside your latest one was smart. It shows visible growth.\n- Your captions are well-structured. The 'What I learned' sentence for each project is specific and insightful.\n\n1 Suggestion:\n- Reorder the projects. Currently: Story → Poster → Video → Infographic → Website. The video between the poster and infographic breaks the design flow. I'd group all Canva work together, then the video, then the website as the capstone.'"
